Morning classes were the same as always.
The sound of chairs scraping the floor.
Half-asleep students pretending to listen.
Sunlight slipping through the windows like it had nothing better to do.
Kaito sat in the back corner of the classroom, chin resting on his hand, eyes half-lidded.
Another day.
Another set of pointless conversations.
Another reminder that nothing really changed.
He wasn’t bullied.
He wasn’t popular.
He just… existed.
And honestly, that was enough.
Peaceful. Quiet. No expectations.
That’s how he liked it.
“Hey, is this seat taken?”
A voice broke through his thoughts.
Kaito didn’t respond at first. He assumed it wasn’t directed at him.
“Hellooo? Earth to quiet guy?”
He slowly turned his head.
A girl stood beside his desk, slightly leaning forward, her eyes bright with curiosity.
New face.
Transfer student, probably.
“…No,” Kaito replied flatly.
She smiled like he had just said something interesting.
“Nice. Then I’ll sit here.”
She dropped her bag onto the chair next to him and sat down like she had already been there for months.
Kaito looked away again.
So much for a quiet morning.
The teacher walked in a few minutes later, starting the usual introduction.
“As you all know, we have a new student joining us today.”
The girl beside him stood up immediately.
“Hi! I’m Hana. Please take care of me!”
Her voice was cheerful. Too cheerful for this early in the morning.
Some students waved. Some nodded.
Kaito didn’t react.
He didn’t need to.
People like her usually found their place quickly.
People like him stayed where they were.
Class started.
Or at least, it was supposed to.
“Hey,” Hana whispered.
Kaito ignored her.
“Hey,” she repeated, poking his arm lightly.
He sighed.
“…What?”
“Why do you look like you hate everything?”
“That’s a weird question.”
“But it’s true, isn’t it?”
“No.”
She tilted her head.
“Then what is it?”
Kaito paused for a second, then answered quietly,
“…I just don’t care.”
Hana stared at him.
Then—she laughed.
Not mockingly. Just… naturally.
“That’s even worse.”
For the rest of the lesson, she kept talking.
Small things.
Random things.
Things that didn’t matter.
And somehow…
He kept answering.
Not much. Just short replies.
But still.
More than usual.
Lunch break.
Kaito stood up and headed for the rooftop like he always did.
It was quiet there.
No unnecessary noise.
No pointless interactions.
Just wind… and space.
Exactly what he needed.
He pushed the door open—
“…Oh.”
Hana was already there.
Sitting on the ground, eating bread like she owned the place.
She looked up and waved.
“Yo.”
“…Why are you here?”
“I like quiet places.”
“…You don’t seem like the quiet type.”
She grinned.
“Maybe I’m full of surprises.”
Kaito clicked his tongue softly and walked past her, leaning against the fence.
For a while…
Neither of them spoke.
Just the sound of the wind.
“This is nice,” Hana said suddenly.
Kaito didn’t reply.
“Being here, I mean. It feels calm.”
“…Yeah.”
It slipped out before he could stop it.
She smiled again.
“See? You do talk.”
“Only when necessary.”
“Am I necessary?”
Kaito paused.
“…No.”
She laughed.
“Cold.”
A few minutes passed.
Then she spoke again, softer this time.
“You know… you’re kinda interesting.”
“I’m not.”
“You are.”
“I’m really not.”
“You are to me.”
That… made him look at her.
For the first time properly.
Her expression wasn’t teasing.
It was genuine.
And that was… unusual.
The bell rang, echoing through the school.
Hana stood up, stretching.
“Guess we should go.”
Kaito nodded.
She picked up her bag, then looked at him.
“Hey.”
“…What?”
“Let’s sit together again tomorrow.”
He frowned slightly.
“…Why?”
She smiled.
“Because I want to.”
Simple.
Too simple.
Before he could respond, she walked ahead, opening the door.
“Don’t be late, okay?”
“…I’m never late.”
“Good. Then I’ll bother you again.”
And just like that—
She left.
Kaito stood there for a moment.
Silent.
Then he sighed.
“…Annoying.”
But as he walked back to class—
For some reason…
The day didn’t feel as boring as usual.